[[File:Akashi-Strait_1.png|thumb|300x300px]] {{coord|34|37|N|134|59|E|scale:1000000|display=title}}
{{Location map | Japan | width = 350 | float = right | caption = Location of the Akashi Strait in Japan | alt = Map of Japan with mark showing location of the Akashi Strait | label = Akashi Strait | lat_deg = 34.6247 | lon_deg = 134.9907 }}
The {{Nihongo|'''Akashi Strait'''|明石海峡|Akashi Kaikyō}} is a [[strait]] between the [[Japanese archipelago|Japanese islands]] of [[Honshu]] and [[Awaji Island|Awaji]]. The strait connects [[Seto Inland Sea]] and [[Osaka Bay]]. The width of the Akashi Strait is approximately 4 kilometers. Its maximum depth is about 110 meters.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jb-honshi.co.jp/english/bridgeworld/bridge.html|title=Akashi-Kaikyo Bridge - Bridge World - Enjoy the top of the Bridge, the LONGEST BRIDGE in the world!|website=www.jb-honshi.co.jp|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref> The utmost tidal current is about {{convert|4.5|m/s|kn|abbr=off}}.<ref name=":0" />
The 1.5 kilometer strait is one of the important points of the Seto Inland Sea and is at the mouth of the [[Pacific Ocean]]. The surrounding waters around Akashi Strait is a known fishery area. The Akashi Strait is designated as an international shipping channel by the Maritime Traffic Safety Act in [[Japan]].<ref name=":0" />
The [[Akashi Kaikyō Bridge]] crosses the strait. This 3.911 kilometer long [[suspension bridge]] links the city of [[Kobe]], the capital of the [[Hyōgo Prefecture]], on [[Honshu|Honshu Island]] to Iwaya on [[Awaji Island]], also within the Hyōgo Prefecture. Its longest span measures 1.991 kilometers.<ref name=":0" /> After 10 years of construction it was finally opened to traffic on 5 April 1998.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadtraffic-technology.com/projects/akashi-kaikyo-bridge-strait-japan/|title=Akashi Kaikyo Bridge, Akashi Strait|website=Road Traffic Technology|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref> At the time of its opening in 1998, it was the world's longest suspension bridge.<ref name=":1" />
The [[Great Hanshin Earthquake]] occurred beneath the Akashi Strait and struck on 17 January 1995 with magnitude 7.2.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=Sr4rfD8Ag-wC&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61&dq=nojima+fault+akashi+strait&source=bl&ots=Y0P8ziRZok&sig=PRLnzJo6MuaCwedM5FZsXrHdIoY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjsrJ-06fjQAhXDFpQKHULDBtA4ChDoAQhGMAs#v=onepage&q=nojima%20fault%20akashi%20strait&f=false|title=Petrophysical Properties of Crystalline Rocks|last=Harvey|first=Peter K.|date=2005-01-01|publisher=Geological Society of London|isbn=9781862391734|language=en}}</ref> The [[Nojima Fault]] is responsible for the [[Great Hanshin earthquake]]. The fault cuts across [[Awaji Island]] and a surface trace of about 10 kilometers long appeared on Awaji Island due to the earthquake.<ref name=":2" /> The Nojima Fault is a branch of the [[Japan Median Tectonic Line]] which runs the length of the southern half of Honshu island. {{Wide image|Akashi-Kaikyo Bridge.JPG|2000px|Panoramic view of the Akashi Strait.}}
