{{short description|A fragment of the Phoenix tectonic plate fused to the Antarctic Peninsula}} The '''Charcot Plate''' was a fragment of the [[Phoenix Plate]].<ref name="eagles">{{Cite journal |authors=Eagles, G., K. Gohl, and R. D. Larter |title=High-resolution animated tectonic reconstruction of the South Pacific and West Antarctic Margin |journal=Geochem. Geophys. Geosyst. |volume=5 |doi=10.1029/2003GC000657 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2003GC000657/full |accessdate=2017-12-11 |date=2004-07-10}}</ref> The Charcot Plate is [[subduct]]ing under [[West Antarctica]]. The subduction of the Charcot Plate stopped before 83 Ma, and became fused onto the [[Antarctic Peninsula]].<ref name="larter">{{cite journal |authors=Larter, R. D., A. P. Cunningham, P. F. Barker, K. Gohl, and F. O. Nitsche |title=Tectonic evolution of the Pacific margin of Antarctica, 1, Late Cretaceous tectonic reconstructions |journal=J. Geophys. Res. |volume=107(B12) |page=2345 |doi=10.1029/2000JB000052 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2000JB000052/full |accessdate=2017-12-11 |date=2002-12-13}}</ref> Researchers have suggested that there are remnants of the western part of the Charcot Plate in the [[Bellingshausen Sea]].<ref name="larter"/>
