'''Edwin Meader''' (September 21, 1909 &ndash; February 1, 2007) was a geography professor at [[Western Michigan University]] and philanthropist.
Born in [[Benton Harbor, Michigan]], Meader moved to [[Kalamazoo]] in 1925.<ref name=wmu>{{cite news |title=WMU mourns death of benefactor Edwin Meader |url=http://www.wmich.edu/wmu/news/2006/11/059.html |work=[[WMU News]] |date= 2007-02-13 |accessdate=2008-03-31 }}</ref> He studied at [[Western Michigan University]] and the [[University of Michigan]], from which he graduated in 1933.<ref name=wmu/> While serving in [[World War II]], Meader visited a University of Michigan excavation area in Egypt, fueling his interest in geography and archaeology.<ref name=wmu/>
After the death of his first wife, Margaret, Meader married [[Mary Meader|Mary Upjohn]] in 1965.<ref name=wmu/> The new couple donated millions of dollars to [[Western Michigan University]], the [[University of Michigan]], and various Kalamazoo charities.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |first=Douglas |last=Martin |title=Mary Meader, 91, Pioneering Aerial Photographer, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/22/us/22meader.html?partner=rssnyt&emc=rss |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= 2008-03-22 |accessdate=2008-03-29 }}</ref> One of their largest gifts was the donation of $4 million to Western Michigan University.<ref name=kala>{{cite news |first=Dave |last=Person |title=Mary Meader lauded as great 20th-century explorer |url=http://blog.mlive.com/kalamazoo_gazette_extra/2008/03/upjohn_heiress_remembered_for.html |work=[[Kalamazoo Gazette]] |date= 2008-03-18 |accessdate=2008-03-29 }}</ref> It resulted in the creation of the W.E. Upjohn Center for the Study of Geographical Change, after her grandfather.<ref name=kala/> It digitizes maps and aerial photographs from all over the world and documents and evaluates geographic changes.<ref name=kala/>
Meader died on February 1, 2007, at the age of 97.<ref name=wmu/> He was survived by his wife Mary, who died March 16, 2008.<ref name=kala/>
