{{Unreliable sources|date=August 2015}}
The '''geographical centre of Earth''' is the [[centroid|geometric centre]] of all land surfaces on [[Earth]]. In a more strict definition, it is the superficial [[barycenter]] of the mass distribution produced by treating each continent or island as a region of a thin shell of uniform density and approximating the [[geoid]] with a sphere. The centre is inside Earth but can be projected to the closest point on the surface.
{{Location map|Earth#Middle East|label=|lat=30|long=31|position=right|float=right|caption= One calculation of the geographical centre of all land surfaces on [[Earth]], lower [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mars-news.de/pyramids/gizacenter3.html|title=Giza, Center of Earth (page 3 of 10)|first=Holger |last=Isenberg |website=mars-news.de|accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref>}}
== History of geo-centroid calculation == In 1864, [[Charles Piazzi Smyth]], Astronomer Royal for Scotland, gave in his book ''Our Inheritance in the Great Pyramid'' the coordinates with {{coord|30|00|N|31|00|E|type:landmark_region:EG_scale:1000000|name=Geographical centre of all land surfaces on Earth (Smyth 1864)|display=inline}}, the location of the [[Great Pyramid of Giza]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Our inheritance in the Great Pyramid|last=Smyth|first=Charles Piazzi|authorlink=Charles Piazzi Smyth|year=1864|publisher=W. Isbister & Co|location=London|pages=V,55,460|url=https://archive.org/details/ourinheritancein00smytuoft}}</ref><ref name="Wilson">{{cite book |title=The Atlantis Blueprint: Unlocking The Ancient Mysteries Of A Long-Lost Civilization |last=Wilson |first=Colin |authorlink=Colin Wilson |author2=Rand Flem-Ath |year=2002 |publisher=[[Random House Digital, Inc.]] |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=63–64 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DS0nS2FFbzcC&pg=PA64&dq=Charles+Smyth+geographical+center&hl=en&sa=X&ei=UIukT_CnB4fA8AS5zM25Aw&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Charles%20Smyth%20&f=false |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> In addition, in October of that year, Smyth proposed to position the [[prime meridian]] at the longitude of the Great Pyramid because there it would "pass over more land than any other". He also argued the cultural significance of the location and its vicinity to Jerusalem. The expert committee deciding the issue, however, voted for Greenwich because "so many ships used the port of London".<ref name="Wilson"/> Referring to Smyth's book, [[Frederick Augustus Porter Barnard]] wrote in his 1884 book, ''The imaginary metrological system of the Great pyramid of Gizeh'', that the perfect location of the Great Pyramid along the longitudinal line could only have been purposefully done by its builders.<ref>{{cite book |title=The imaginary metrological system of the Great pyramid of Gizeh |last=Barnard |first=Frederick Augustus Porter |authorlink=Frederick Augustus Porter Barnard |year=1884 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=12–13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ww7gAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA13&dq=%22geographical+center%22+earth+pyramid&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HZakT4eTFYeO8wTf4-y8Aw&ved=0CEsQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=geographical%20center%20earth%20pyramid&f=false |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>
In the September 1919 issue of ''Trestle Board Magazine'', [[Freemasonry|Mason]] William Galliher stated that knowledge of the Great Pyramid being the geographical centre was "determined by many years of scientific investigation" and that the Great Pyramid was likely to be the "last of the present land surface of the earth" to survive a cataclysmic event, due to its positioning.<ref>{{cite journal |author=William Galliher |date=September 1919 |title=The Riddle of Cheops Pyramid |journal=Trestle Board Magazine |volume=33 |issue=3 |pages=9 |publisher=[[Kessinger Publishing]] |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e4bGA0Ss5VwC&pg=PT18&dq=%22geographical+center%22+earth&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LZCkT53OGZSi8QTik5HXAw&ved=0CFgQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=geographical%20center%20earth&f=false |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>
In 1973, Andrew J. Woods, a physicist with [[General Atomics|Gulf Energy & Environmental Systems]] in San Diego, used a digital global map and calculated the coordinates on a mainframe system as {{coord|39|00|N|34|00|E|type:landmark_scale:1000000|name=Geographical centre of all land surfaces on Earth (Woods 1973)|display=inline}}, in modern Turkey, 1,000&nbsp;km north of Giza.<ref name="Woods">{{cite book|series=I.C.R. Technical Monographs|volume=3|title=The Center of the Earth|last=Woods|first=Andrew J.|year=1973|publisher=I.C.R.|location=London|url=http://www.icr.org/article/50/}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=This is a non-science website.|date=August 2015}} In 2003, a similar result was yielded by Holger Isenberg: 40°52'0"N, 34°34'0"E.<ref>Isenberg, Holger. ''Giza: Centre of Earth'', page 5, 2003. http://mars-news.de/pyramids/gizacenter5.html</ref> In 2016, [[Google Maps]] marked 40°52′N 34°34′E as the geographic centre of the world. <ref>http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/google-marks-turkeys-corum-as-center-of-the-earth-100514</ref>
In 2007, [[Susan Wise Bauer]] claimed in her book '' Earliest Accounts to the Fall of Rome'', that the theory that the Great Pyramid was the geographical centre of Earth would only hold true if a [[Mercator projection]] is used as the map for Earth, which was "unlikely to have been a common practice of the ancient Egyptians".<ref>{{cite book |title=The History of the Ancient World: From the Earliest Accounts to the Fall of Rome |last=Bauer |first=Susan Wise |authorlink=Susan Wise Bauer |year=2007 |publisher=[[W. W. Norton & Company]] |location= |isbn= |page=86 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HmShg3dnLSMC&pg=PA86&dq=%22geographical+center%22+earth+pyramid&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HZakT4eTFYeO8wTf4-y8Aw&ved=0CFwQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22geographical%20center%22%20earth%20pyramid&f=false |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref>
