'''Giovanni Leardo''' was a 15th-century Venetian geographer and cosmographer. Leardo made at least four [[mappae mundi]], of which three survive today.<ref name="Edson2007">{{cite book|author=Evelyn Edson|title=The World Map, 1300-1492: The Persistence of Tradition and Transformation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dhgYlhXJy_QC&pg=PA188|year=2007|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-8589-1|pages=188–}}</ref>

Leardo's 1442 map is held at the Biblioteca Communale Library in [[Verona]]. A 1447 map does not survive, but a 1448 map is held at the [[Palazzo Chiericati|Museo Civico]] at [[Vicenza]].<ref>Jim Siebold, [http://cartographic-images.net/Cartographic_Images/242_Leardo_World_Maps.html The Leardo World Maps]</ref> A 1452 map was donated by [[Archer M. Huntington]] to the [[American Geographical Society]], and is the oldest world map in the library there.<ref name="WrightHoen1928">{{cite book|last=Wright|first=John Kirtland|authorlink=John Kirtland Wright|title=The Leardo map of the world: 1452 or 1453, in the collections of the American geographical society|year=1928|publisher=American Geographical Society}}</ref>

